    <p>Notice that each time <m>x</m> increases by <m>1</m>, <m>y</m> increases by the same amount. We call this kind of relationship a <term>linear relationship</term>. This is because if we plot points in the table, we will get a line (to be covered in later sections).</p>

    <p>To describe a linear relationship, we use a <term>linear equation</term>, which, in most cases, is in the form of <men>y=mx+b</men></p>

    <p>The number <m>m</m>, which is in front of <m>x</m> in the equation, is called <term>rate of change</term>, or <term>slope</term>. In <xref ref="table-pattern-two-x-plus-one">Table</xref>, we can see each time when <m>x</m> increases by <m>1</m>, <m>y</m> increases by <m>2</m>. We say data in the table has a linear relationship, and the rate of change is <m>2</m>. The corresponding linear equation would look like <m>y=2x+b</m>.</p>

    <p>The number <m>b</m> in the equation <m>y=mx+b</m> is called the <term>starting value</term>, or <term><m>y</m>-intercept</term>. A linear equation's starting value is its <m>y</m> value when <m>x=0</m> (thus the name <q>starting value</q>). In <xref ref="table-pattern-two-x-plus-one">Table</xref>, we can see when <m>x=0</m>, <m>y=1</m>. Now we can write the equation <m>y=2x+1</m>.</p>

    <p>We can understand the equation <m>y=2x+1</m> in this way: Starting at <m>y=1</m>, each time when <m>x</m>-value increases by <m>1</m>, the <m>y</m>-value increases by <m>2</m>.</p>

    <p>Now you should be able to find a linear equation for the second table and the third table in <xref ref="example-table-patterns">Example</xref>. However, in the fourth table, we have:</p>

