              <cell><m>y</m><nbsp />increases by <m>6</m></cell> 
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>2</m></cell>
              <cell><m>2</m></cell>
              <cell/>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>x</m><nbsp />increases by <m>3</m></cell> 
              <cell/>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>y</m><nbsp />increases by <m>9</m></cell> 
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>5</m></cell>
              <cell><m>11</m></cell>
            <cell/>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>x</m><nbsp />increases by <m>4</m></cell> 
              <cell/>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>y</m><nbsp />increases by <m>12</m></cell> 
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>9</m></cell>
              <cell><m>23</m></cell>
              <cell/>
            </row>
          </tabular>
     	  </table>

        <p>Note that the increase of <m>y</m>-values are not consistent. However, when we judge whether a relationship is linear, we judge by the <term>rate of change</term>.</p>

        <list>
          <title>Finding the rate of change</title>
            <ul>
              <li>When <m>x</m> increases by <m>2</m>, <m>y</m> increases by <m>6</m>. This implies the rate of change is <m>\frac{6}{2}=3</m>.</li>
              <li>When <m>x</m> increases by <m>3</m>, <m>y</m> increases by <m>9</m>. This implies the rate of change is <m>\frac{9}{3}=3</m>.</li>
              <li>When <m>x</m> increases by <m>4</m>, <m>y</m> increases by <m>12</m>. This implies the rate of change is <m>\frac{12}{4}=3</m>.</li>
            </ul>
        </list>

        <p>Since the rate of change (or slope) is consistent, the data does have a linear relationship. The linear equation looks like <m>y=3x+b</m>.</p>

        <p>According to the table, when <m>x=0, y=-4</m>. Since the starting value (or <m>y</m>-intercept) is <m>-4</m>. The linear equation is <m>y=3x-4</m>.</p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>Decide whether data in the table has a linear relationship. If so, write the linear equation in the form of <m>y=mx+b</m>.</p>
        <table>
          <caption>Does the data have a linear relationship?</caption>
          <tabular>
            <col halign="center" />
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>x</m>-values</cell>
              <cell><m>y</m>-values</cell>
            </row>
