        </table>    
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <table>
          <caption>Does the data have a linear relationship?</caption>
          <tabular>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row>
              <cell bottom="medium"/>
              <cell bottom="medium"><m>x</m>-values</cell>
              <cell bottom="medium"><m>y</m>-values</cell>
              <cell bottom="medium"/>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>3</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
              <cell/>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>x</m><nbsp />increases by <m>3</m></cell> 
              <cell/>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>y</m><nbsp />decreases by <m>6</m></cell> 
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>6</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-8</m></cell>
              <cell/>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>x</m><nbsp />increases by <m>2</m></cell> 
              <cell/>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>y</m><nbsp />decreases by <m>4</m></cell> 
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>8</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-12</m></cell>
            <cell/>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>x</m><nbsp />increases by <m>3</m></cell> 
              <cell/>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>y</m><nbsp />decreases by <m>6</m></cell> 
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>11</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-18</m></cell>
              <cell/>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>Note that the decrease of <m>y</m>-values are not consistent. However, when we judge whether a relationship is linear, we judge by the <term>rate of change</term>.</p>

        <list>
          <title>Finding the rate of change</title>
            <ul>
              <li>When <m>x</m> increases by <m>3</m>, <m>y</m> decreases by <m>6</m>. This implies the rate of change is <m>\frac{-6}{3}=-2</m>.</li>
              <li>When <m>x</m> increases by <m>2</m>, <m>y</m> decreases by <m>4</m>. This implies the rate of change is <m>\frac{-4}{2}=-2</m>.</li>
              <li>When <m>x</m> increases by <m>3</m> again, <m>y</m> decreases by <m>6</m> again. This implies the rate of change is <m>\frac{-6}{3}=-2</m>.</li>
            </ul>
        </list>

        <p>Since the rate of change (or slope) is consistent, the data does have a linear relationship. The linear equation looks like <m>y=-2x+b</m>.</p>

        <p>The challenge is that we don't see the starting value (<m>y</m>-intercept) in the table, which is the <m>y</m> value when <m>x=0</m>. Fortunately, once we find the rate of change, we can go backward from the first row, <m>(3,-2)</m>, and figure out the starting value:</p>

        <table>
          <caption>Does the data have a linear relationship?</caption>
          <tabular>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row>
              <cell bottom="medium"/>
              <cell bottom="medium"><m>x</m>-values</cell>
              <cell bottom="medium"><m>y</m>-values</cell>
              <cell bottom="medium"/>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>\vdots</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\vdots</m></cell>
              <cell/>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>0</m></cell>
              <cell><m>4</m></cell>
              <cell/>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>x</m><nbsp />increases by <m>1</m></cell> 
              <cell/>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>y</m><nbsp />decreases by <m>2</m></cell> 
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>2</m></cell>
              <cell/>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>x</m><nbsp />increases by <m>1</m></cell> 
              <cell/>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>y</m><nbsp />decreases by <m>2</m></cell> 
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>2</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0</m></cell>
            <cell/>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>x</m><nbsp />increases by <m>1</m></cell> 
              <cell/>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>y</m><nbsp />decreases by <m>2</m></cell> 
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>3</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
              <cell/>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>\vdots</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\vdots</m></cell>
              <cell/>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </table>

        <p>According to the table, when <m>x=0, y=4</m>. Since the starting value (or <m>y</m>-intercept) is <m>4</m>. The linear equation is <m>y=-2x+4</m>.</p>
      </solution>
